{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c789b1b8-da74-4b8f-a1c6-4103ff52096f","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You can find them in:\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — user-level crashes\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-level crashes\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_macOS.ips`.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them visually.\n\n**For core dumps**, macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n```\n\nThen re-run your app — a core dump will be written to `/tmp/` on crash.\n\n> 💡 The `.ips` crash log is usually sufficient for initial triage — it contains the faulting thread's native backtrace, signal info, and loaded libraries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0c219211-ccf9-4623-bc78-8fdb92a04ca9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search a codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":311,"requestId":"608A:1230E4:2CA60F:3A4771:69FFE3D5"},"id":"f2a2f126-68c0-4b0d-a1f7-391baf7189f0","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:48:14.378Z","parentId":"ab72cc29-78fa-4480-bb82-6b670d761e43"}
